Problems found
==============

1. Unnecessary `async` / blocking call  
   • `jwt.verify()` is being invoked **synchronously**.  
   • Marking the wrapper `async` adds nothing but implies that the
     function is non-blocking when it is not.  
   • With large RSA/ECDSA keys the sync version can block the event-loop.

2. Swallowing every error  
   • All kinds of failures (token absent, expired, malformed, wrong
     signature, internal library error, even programming errors) are
     turned into the same harmless looking `null`.  
   • This hides bugs from you and makes debugging and monitoring hard.  
   • A logic error inside `jwt.verify` could also be masked and go
     unnoticed.

3. No validation options  
   • You do not restrict the accepted signing algorithm.  An attacker can
     send a token signed with `none` or a weaker algorithm if the signing
     secret accidently leaks.  
   • `aud`, `iss`, `sub`, `nbf`, clock tolerance, etc. are not checked.

4. Symmetric secret is used indiscriminately  
   • The same key that signs tokens is placed on the service that only
     needs to verify them.  If that service is compromised the attacker
     can now mint valid tokens.  
   • Better use an **asymmetric** algorithm (`RS256`, `ES256`) and store
     only the public key on the verifier.

5. No input sanity checks  
   • Non-string values (`undefined`, objects) passed as `token` will make
     `jwt.verify` throw.  You rely on the catch block to hide that.

6. Silent failure ≠ secure failure  
   • Returning `null` gives no clue to the caller why verification failed
     and makes it easy to accidentally treat “no user” the same as
     “unauthenticated”.

7. Potential information leak  
   • The decoded “user” object is returned without any filtering.  If the
     token contains unexpected claims (e.g. `roles`, `admin: true`)
     higher layers may trust them blindly.

8. No logging / monitoring  
   • You lose the ability to detect abuse such as repeated token replay,
     tokens from wrong issuer, etc.

How to fix it
=============

1. Use the asynchronous verifier (non-blocking)

```js
const util   = require('util');
const verify = util.promisify(jwt.verify);     // turns callback API into Promise
```

2. Validate input early

```js
function ensureString(value, name) {
  if (typeof value !== 'string' || value.trim() === '') {
    throw new TypeError(`${name} must be a non-empty string`);
  }
}
```

3. Harden verification options

```js
const VERIFY_OPTS = {
  algorithms : ['RS256'],                 // accept only what you issue
  audience   : process.env.JWT_AUDIENCE,  // expected aud claim
  issuer     : process.env.JWT_ISSUER,    // expected iss claim
  clockTolerence: 60                      // seconds leeway
};
```

4. Give meaningful errors (or map them to HTTP codes)

```js
class AuthError extends Error { constructor(msg) { super(msg); this.name='AuthError'; } }
```

5. Put it together

```js
const logger = require('./logger');   // however you log

async function authenticate(token) {
  ensureString(token, 'token');

  try {
    // Public key only – do NOT keep the private key here
    const publicKey = process.env.JWT_PUBLIC_KEY;
    const payload   = await verify(token, publicKey, VERIFY_OPTS);

    // Optionally whitelist claims you actually use
    return {
      id   : payload.sub,
      email: payload.email,
      role : payload.role
    };

  } catch (err) {
    // log once; do not expose internals to the client
    logger.warn({ err }, 'JWT verification failed');
    throw new AuthError('Invalid or expired token');
  }
}
```

6. Callers now get an exception they can translate to a
   401/403 HTTP response, not `null`:

```js
try {
  const user = await authenticate(req.cookies.token);
  req.user = user;
  next();
} catch (e) {
  res.status(401).json({ error: e.message });
}
```

Additional recommendations
--------------------------

• Rotate keys regularly and keep current public keys in memory, not
  environment variables only.  
• Use `helmet`, `rate-limit` middlewares to slow down brute-force token
  guessing.  
• Consider short-lived access tokens plus refresh tokens instead of one
  long-lived JWT.  
• Run `npm audit` and keep the `jsonwebtoken` package updated; older
  versions had algorithm-confusion vulnerabilities.

With these changes the authentication routine is non-blocking, explicit
about what it accepts, fails noisily for the developer but safely for
the client, and does not expose signing keys where they are not needed.
